---
import JapanPitchLayout from '@layouts/JapanPitchLayout.astro';
import Map from '@components/Map.astro';
import japanRegions from '@data/japan-regions.json';
import japanRoute from '@data/japan-route.json';
---

<JapanPitchLayout
  title="Japan — Landscape, Heritage, Craft"
  description="A self-produced photography project. Autumn 2026."
>

  <!-- ======= 1. Cover ======= -->
  <section class="slide slide--jp-hero" id="slide-1">
    <div class="slide__inner">
      <p class="slide__overline reveal">Heist Studio</p>
      <h1 class="jp-hero-title reveal">Japan</h1>
      <p class="slide__subtitle reveal">Landscape. Heritage. Craft.</p>
      <p class="slide__mark fade-in">Autumn 2026</p>
    </div>
    <div class="scroll-hint fade-in">
      <div class="scroll-hint__arrow"></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 2. The Thesis ======= -->
  <section class="slide" id="slide-2">
    <div class="slide__inner stagger-children">
      <h2 class="slide__heading">The Thesis</h2>
      <p class="slide__text">
        A blacksmith forges a hoe. A farmer uses that hoe for forty years until the
        handle is worn to the shape of her grip. The vegetables she grows are carried
        to a kitchen where the same knife has prepared the same dish for three generations.
        The meal arrives on lacquerware that took longer to make than the building it&rsquo;s
        served in.
      </p>
      <p class="slide__text">
        In rural Japan, this chain is unbroken. Forge to field to harvest to table.
        Every link is visible, every hand known by name. <strong>This is a country where
        craft is not separated from daily life</strong>&mdash;it is daily life. And the
        landscape that makes these places hard to reach is the same landscape that
        preserved them.
      </p>
      <p class="slide__text">
        Three ideas recur everywhere we look. The <strong>deliberate act</strong>&mdash;craft
        meeting chaos, precision existing inside disorder. The <strong>pause</strong>&mdash;ma,
        the negative space that gives meaning to what surrounds it. And <strong>patina</strong>&mdash;wabi-sabi,
        the beauty of surfaces shaped by age, weather, and use. Three lenses trained on the same
        subject: <strong>a place that time forgot, and that forgot nothing.</strong>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 3. Three Lenses ======= -->
  <section class="slide" id="slide-3">
    <div class="slide__inner">
      <h2 class="slide__heading reveal">Three Lenses</h2>
      <div class="jp-lenses-grid stagger-children">
        <div class="jp-lens">
          <div class="jp-lens__title">Craft &amp; Chaos</div>
          <p class="jp-lens__text">
            A blacksmith hammers a sickle blade in a forge that hasn&rsquo;t changed in
            two centuries. A farmer sharpens it on a stone her grandmother used. The
            same impulse that produces hand-forged steel produces neon-lit pachinko
            parlors&mdash;obsessive precision applied to completely different ends. The
            tension between them is the photograph.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-lens">
          <div class="jp-lens__title">Ma (間)</div>
          <p class="jp-lens__text">
            Negative space as intention. The pause between brush strokes. The silence in
            a temple garden that makes the birdsong louder. The 4am calm before the fish
            market wakes. Ma is not emptiness&mdash;it is the interval that gives form to
            everything around it.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-lens">
          <div class="jp-lens__title">Patina</div>
          <p class="jp-lens__text">
            Wabi-sabi applied to the lens. A kitchen counter scored by sixty years of
            the same knife. Noren curtains bleached by decades of sun. The worn handle
            of a hoe that has turned the same soil since the war. Japan does not
            restore&mdash;it lets time become part of the surface. The beauty is in the use.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="jp-rule"></div>
      <p class="acts-coda fade-in">Not three separate stories. Three ways of seeing the same one.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 4. The Manifesto ======= -->
  <section class="slide" id="slide-4">
    <div class="slide__inner stagger-children">
      <h2 class="slide__heading">The Manifesto</h2>
      <p class="slide__text">
        Seven to ten days. Three photographers. One thesis. These are the rules
        we hold ourselves to.
      </p>
      <ul class="jp-manifesto">
        <li>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__num">01</span>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__rule">This is a photography project that happens in Japan. Not a trip with cameras. The distinction matters.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__num">02</span>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__rule">Commit to the thesis before landing. Every frame serves the story or it doesn&rsquo;t get made.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__num">03</span>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__rule">Slow glass, slow pace. Manual focus forces you to the rhythm of the subject. Match it.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__num">04</span>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__rule">Stay in ryokan. The architecture, the meals, the rhythm of a traditional inn&mdash;these are not accommodation. They are content.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__num">05</span>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__rule">Cull daily. Edit daily. Don&rsquo;t come home to three thousand unprocessed RAW files. The discipline is part of the craft.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__num">06</span>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__rule">Build a rhythm. Morning golden hour. Midday interiors and details. Evening atmosphere. Repeat.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__num">07</span>
          <span class="jp-manifesto__rule">Come back with a series, not a highlight reel. Twelve to twenty frames that tell one story in one visual language.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 5. Visual Direction — Keywords ======= -->
  <section class="slide slide--jp-keywords" id="slide-5">
    <div class="slide__inner">
      <p class="slide__overline reveal">Visual Direction</p>
      <p class="jp-keywords fade-in">
        craft &middot; contrast &middot; stillness &middot; patina &middot;
        steam &middot; rain &middot; texture &middot; intimate &middot;
        precision &middot; harvest &middot; forge &middot;
        pilgrimage &middot; neon &middot; moss &middot; iron
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 6. Visual Direction — Language ======= -->
  <section class="slide" id="slide-6">
    <div class="slide__inner stagger-children">
      <p class="slide__overline">Visual Direction</p>
      <h2 class="slide__heading">The Language</h2>
      <p class="slide__text">
        This is not the wide-landscape adventure photography aesthetic. Japan requires
        a different mode entirely&mdash;closer to Masao Yamamoto than to National Geographic.
      </p>
      <ul class="equipment-list">
        <li><strong>Intimate framing</strong> &mdash; hands, steam, texture, light through paper. Get close.</li>
        <li><strong>Available light</strong> &mdash; neon bleed, paper lanterns, fluorescent kissaten interiors, overcast diffusion. The ambient light is the story.</li>
        <li><strong>Reflections &amp; layers</strong> &mdash; rain on asphalt, neon in puddles, lacquer surfaces, glass and steel multiplying light sources.</li>
        <li><strong>Natural framing</strong> &mdash; torii gates, machiya doorways, alley corridors. Japan builds its own compositions.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 7. Visual Direction — Color Palette ======= -->
  <section class="slide" id="slide-7">
    <div class="slide__inner stagger-children">
      <p class="slide__overline">Visual Direction</p>
      <h2 class="slide__heading">Color Palette</h2>
      <p class="slide__text">
        Move away from warm desaturated palettes. Japan&rsquo;s color story is its own.
      </p>
      <div class="jp-palette stagger-children">
        <div class="jp-palette__swatch" style="background:#100F0F;">
          <span class="jp-palette__name">Sumi Ink</span>
          <span class="jp-palette__note">deep blacks, shadow, night</span>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-palette__swatch" style="background:#282726;">
          <span class="jp-palette__name">Charcoal</span>
          <span class="jp-palette__note">concrete, volcanic stone, temple roofs</span>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-palette__swatch" style="background:#879A39; color:#1C1B1A;">
          <span class="jp-palette__name">Moss</span>
          <span class="jp-palette__note">temple gardens, bamboo, forest floor</span>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-palette__swatch" style="background:#DA702C;">
          <span class="jp-palette__name">Hinoki</span>
          <span class="jp-palette__note">warm wood, autumn, lacquer glow</span>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-palette__swatch" style="background:#D14D41;">
          <span class="jp-palette__name">Vermillion</span>
          <span class="jp-palette__note">torii gates, forge heat, neon</span>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-palette__swatch" style="background:#4385BE;">
          <span class="jp-palette__name">Indigo</span>
          <span class="jp-palette__note">dyed fabric, twilight, rain</span>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-palette__swatch" style="background:#F2F0E5; color:#1C1B1A;">
          <span class="jp-palette__name">Washi</span>
          <span class="jp-palette__note">paper, rice, steam, overcast light</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 8. The Route ======= -->
  <section class="slide slide--jp-map-timeline" id="slide-8">
    <div class="jp-map-timeline__timeline">
      <h2 class="slide__heading">The Route</h2>
      <p class="jp-timeline__subtitle">The Japan that requires asking for directions.</p>
      <div class="jp-timeline">
        <div class="jp-timeline__phase" data-region-num="05">
          <div class="jp-timeline__dates">Oct 1</div>
          <div class="jp-timeline__content">
            <div class="jp-timeline__label">Arrive</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__location">Kanazawa</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__desc">Base camp. Meet local fixer. Settle into ryokan. Scout the Higashi chaya district.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-timeline__phase jp-timeline__phase--active" data-region-num="01">
          <div class="jp-timeline__dates">Oct 2&ndash;4</div>
          <div class="jp-timeline__content">
            <div class="jp-timeline__label">Shooting</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__location">Noto Peninsula</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__desc">Wajima lacquerware studios, morning market at dawn, fishing villages. Terraced rice harvest. Ryokan each night.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-timeline__phase jp-timeline__phase--active" data-region-num="02">
          <div class="jp-timeline__dates">Oct 5&ndash;6</div>
          <div class="jp-timeline__content">
            <div class="jp-timeline__label">Shooting</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__location">Echizen &middot; Takefu</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__desc">Blacksmith forges, washi papermaking, farm-to-table chain. The complete craft loop.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-timeline__phase jp-timeline__phase--active" data-region-num="03">
          <div class="jp-timeline__dates">Oct 7&ndash;8</div>
          <div class="jp-timeline__content">
            <div class="jp-timeline__label">Shooting</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__location">Kamikochi &middot; Kita Alps</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__desc">Azusa River valley, autumn color, mountain huts. Alpine clarity before the passes close.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-timeline__phase jp-timeline__phase--active" data-region-num="04">
          <div class="jp-timeline__dates">Oct 9&ndash;11</div>
          <div class="jp-timeline__content">
            <div class="jp-timeline__label">Shooting</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__location">Kii Peninsula &middot; Kumano Kod&#333;</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__desc">Cedar pilgrimage trail. Walk the Nakahechi. Shrine architecture, waterfall light. Pilgrim ryokan.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-timeline__phase">
          <div class="jp-timeline__dates">Oct 12</div>
          <div class="jp-timeline__content">
            <div class="jp-timeline__label">Edit &middot; Buffer</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__location">Flexible</div>
            <div class="jp-timeline__desc">Cull and edit. Revisit if needed. Begin sequencing.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="jp-map-timeline__map">
      <Map
        center={[136.8, 35.8]}
        zoom={6.8}
        interactive={false}
        class="jp-map-full"
        regions={japanRegions as any}
        route={japanRoute as any}
        markers={[
          { lng: 136.969, lat: 37.228, label: 'Noto', num: '01', target: 'slide-9' },
          { lng: 136.177, lat: 35.890, label: 'Echizen', num: '02', target: 'slide-11' },
          { lng: 137.615, lat: 36.222, label: 'Kamikochi', num: '03', target: 'slide-8' },
          { lng: 135.480, lat: 33.767, label: 'Kii Peninsula', num: '04', target: 'slide-10' },
          { lng: 136.632, lat: 36.574, label: 'Kanazawa', num: '05', target: 'slide-8' },
        ]}
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 9. Location — Noto Peninsula ======= -->
  <section class="slide slide--location slide--noto" id="slide-9">
    <div class="slide__inner stagger-children">
      <p class="slide__overline">Location</p>
      <h2 class="slide__heading">Noto Peninsula</h2>
      <p class="slide__text">
        The Noto Peninsula juts into the Japan Sea like a place that forgot to modernize.
        Wajima&rsquo;s lacquerware artisans apply urushi in coats so thin they are measured in
        fractions of a millimeter&mdash;thirty layers over thirty years. The morning market has
        run without interruption for a thousand years. The fishing villages along the coast are
        exactly as weathered and beautiful as they should be.
      </p>
      <p class="slide__text">
        This is where craft and patina converge. The lacquer is precision. The village is time.
      </p>
      <div class="location-meta">
        <div class="location-meta__item">
          <div class="location-meta__key">Craft</div>
          <div class="location-meta__value">Urushi lacquerware, Wajima</div>
        </div>
        <div class="location-meta__item">
          <div class="location-meta__key">Stay</div>
          <div class="location-meta__value">Ryokan &mdash; tatami, onsen, kaiseki</div>
        </div>
        <div class="location-meta__item">
          <div class="location-meta__key">The lens</div>
          <div class="location-meta__value">Patina &mdash; time on every surface</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 10. Location — Kii Peninsula ======= -->
  <section class="slide slide--location slide--kii" id="slide-10">
    <div class="slide__inner stagger-children">
      <p class="slide__overline">Location</p>
      <h2 class="slide__heading">Kii Peninsula &middot; Kumano Kod&#333;</h2>
      <p class="slide__text">
        The Kumano Kod&#333; is a UNESCO pilgrimage route through ancient cedar forest.
        The trees are eight hundred years old and the trail has been walked for twelve hundred.
        The light through the canopy falls in columns. The shrines at the trail&rsquo;s end exist
        because a thousand years of walkers decided they should.
      </p>
      <p class="slide__text">
        The villages along the Nakahechi survive because of pilgrims&mdash;the food, the inns,
        the shrines. Walk slowly and they open.
      </p>
      <div class="location-meta">
        <div class="location-meta__item">
          <div class="location-meta__key">Craft</div>
          <div class="location-meta__value">Cedar woodwork, shrine architecture</div>
        </div>
        <div class="location-meta__item">
          <div class="location-meta__key">Stay</div>
          <div class="location-meta__value">Pilgrim ryokan &mdash; 1,200 years of hosting walkers</div>
        </div>
        <div class="location-meta__item">
          <div class="location-meta__key">The lens</div>
          <div class="location-meta__value">Ma &mdash; silence between ancient trees</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 11. The Craftsmen ======= -->
  <section class="slide" id="slide-11">
    <div class="slide__inner stagger-children">
      <h2 class="slide__heading">The Craftsmen</h2>
      <p class="slide__text">
        The craftsmen are not in the cities. They are in Wajima because the climate is right for
        lacquer. In Echizen because the water is right for paper. In Takefu because the steel is
        right for knives. The geography that makes these places hard to reach is the same geography
        that made the craft possible.
      </p>
      <p class="slide__text">
        <strong>Follow one chain from forge to table and every link is a photograph.</strong>
      </p>
      <ul class="equipment-list">
        <li><strong>Blacksmiths</strong> &mdash; Takefu, Echizen &middot; hand-forging sickles, hoes, and kitchen knives in the same workshops for generations. The implements that make the food chain possible.</li>
        <li><strong>Farmers</strong> &mdash; terraced rice paddies, mountain vegetable plots &middot; maintaining crops with hand tools, harvesting by season. The landscape shaped by centuries of the same work.</li>
        <li><strong>The table</strong> &mdash; farm-to-table is not a concept here, it&rsquo;s a geography &middot; the kitchen is minutes from the field, the knife was forged in the next village, the lacquerware was made down the road.</li>
        <li><strong>Urushi lacquerware</strong> &mdash; Wajima, Noto Peninsula &middot; 0.1mm coats, climate-bound, thirty-year application. The vessel the meal arrives on.</li>
        <li><strong>Echizen washi</strong> &mdash; Echizen, Fukui Prefecture &middot; handmade paper from 1,500 years of mountain water</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 12. The Instruments ======= -->
  <section class="slide" id="slide-12">
    <div class="slide__inner stagger-children">
      <h2 class="slide__heading">The Instruments</h2>
      <p class="slide__text">
        Two Canon R bodies. Two Leica Summicron-R primes adapted to RF mount.
        Manual focus, manual intention. The slow glass forces the photographer
        to the pace of the subject.
      </p>
      <ul class="equipment-list">
        <li>
          <strong>Canon EOS R5 Mark II + EOS R5</strong> &mdash; Two-body system. The R5 II
          for primary work, the R5 as second angle or backup. Dual bodies mean no lens
          swaps in the field&mdash;one wide, one standard, both ready.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Leica Summicron-R 35mm f/2 + 50mm f/2</strong> &mdash; Adapted to Canon RF.
          Manual focus only. The Summicron rendering&mdash;controlled, precise, with a
          character that modern autofocus glass doesn&rsquo;t reproduce&mdash;matches the
          project&rsquo;s thesis. Craft tools for a craft story. The 35 for context, the 50
          for portraits and detail.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>RF 35mm f/1.4 L VCM</strong> &mdash; Native AF lens for when speed matters.
          Night work, moving subjects, moments that won&rsquo;t wait for manual focus.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Leica Q2</strong> &mdash; 28mm compact. Personal camera, not the primary
          instrument. For the moments between the moments.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p class="slide__text">
        <strong>The slow glass is the point.</strong> Vintage Leica primes on modern bodies
        enforce a deliberate pace&mdash;the same intentionality the craftsmen bring to their
        own tools. No zooms on the primary kit. No drone.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 13. The Crew ======= -->
  <section class="slide" id="slide-13">
    <div class="slide__inner">
      <h2 class="slide__heading reveal">The Crew</h2>
      <p class="slide__text reveal">
        Self-produced. Three photographers, one local fixer. Every night in a ryokan.
      </p>
      <div class="jp-crew-grid stagger-children">
        <div class="jp-crew-card">
          <div class="jp-crew-card__name">Corbin</div>
          <div class="jp-crew-card__role">Director / Lead Photographer</div>
          <p class="jp-crew-card__text">
            Creative direction, primary shooter, editorial output. Second trip to Japan&mdash;first
            as producer. Background in adventure and documentary photography across five Strohl
            retreats (Montana, Pyrenees, Ard&egrave;che, Dolomites).
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-crew-card">
          <div class="jp-crew-card__name">Kyle Tubbs</div>
          <div class="jp-crew-card__role">Photographer / Producer</div>
          <p class="jp-crew-card__text">
            Production, logistics, second camera. Co-architect of the route, the thesis, and the
            partnership strategy. The operational backbone.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-crew-card">
          <div class="jp-crew-card__name">Matthew James Price</div>
          <div class="jp-crew-card__role">Photographer</div>
          <p class="jp-crew-card__text">
            Third eye, different perspective. Brings a distinct visual voice to the same subject
            matter&mdash;the series is richer for the contrast.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="jp-crew-card">
          <div class="jp-crew-card__name">Local Fixer</div>
          <div class="jp-crew-card__role">Producer / Translator</div>
          <p class="jp-crew-card__text">
            Japanese-speaking producer sourced before arrival. Coordinates artisan access, translates,
            navigates cultural protocol. The difference between photographing a workshop and being
            invited into one.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 14. Deliverables ======= -->
  <section class="slide" id="slide-14">
    <div class="slide__inner stagger-children">
      <h2 class="slide__heading">Deliverables</h2>
      <ul class="deliverables-list">
        <li>
          <span class="deliverable__name">The Series</span>
          <span class="deliverable__desc">12&ndash;20 final images, edited and sequenced as a cohesive body of work. One thesis. One visual language.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="deliverable__name">Zine Concept</span>
          <span class="deliverable__desc">Self-published photo zine &mdash; layout, sequence, and print-ready design. Even if it doesn&rsquo;t print on this trip, design it.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="deliverable__name">Substack Series</span>
          <span class="deliverable__desc">3&ndash;4 essays: the thesis, craft profiles, visual diary, production retrospective.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="deliverable__name">Print Candidates</span>
          <span class="deliverable__desc">3&ndash;5 images suitable for large-format fine art printing.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="deliverable__name">Production Docs</span>
          <span class="deliverable__desc">What worked, what didn&rsquo;t. Location research, contact sheets, process documentation. Feed back into the next project.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 15. Partnership Fit ======= -->
  <section class="slide" id="slide-15">
    <div class="slide__inner">
      <h2 class="slide__heading reveal">Partnership Fit</h2>
      <p class="slide__text reveal">
        The project is self-funded and self-directed. But the structure is modular&mdash;each
        element can align with a brand partner without compromising the thesis.
      </p>
      <div class="partnership-grid stagger-children">
        <div class="partner">
          <div class="partner__name">Canon</div>
          <p class="partner__angle">
            Two R5 bodies as the backbone. Vintage Leica glass adapted to RF&mdash;old
            craft meeting new capability. A story about intentional tools.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="partner">
          <div class="partner__name">Hospitality &middot; Ryokan</div>
          <p class="partner__angle">
            Traditional inns as base camps for the entire trip. The architecture is the
            content&mdash;tatami, fusuma, onsen steam, kaiseki. Coverage that opens rooms for years.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="partner">
          <div class="partner__name">Craft Brands</div>
          <p class="partner__angle">
            Artisan partnerships: lacquerware, washi, knives, ironware. Product as story.
            The maker&rsquo;s hands are the photograph.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="partner">
          <div class="partner__name">Editorial &middot; Publishing</div>
          <p class="partner__angle">
            The craft essay, the pilgrimage series, the patina portfolio&mdash;each stands
            alone as a feature commission for Monocle, Wallpaper*, or Cereal.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======= 16. Close ======= -->
